lg.l: I can't forbear mentioning (now I have an Opportunity), the Pleasure I had in reading a Beautiful Poem, call'd Cadenus and Vancessa, writ by Dr. Swift, a Person very well known, and of too much Merit to be describ'd by any Body but himself. But as the Moral, which may be drawn from this Ingenious Piece, is worth the attention of my female Readers, I must earnestly recommend it to them. In the mean Time I shall take the Liberty to transcribe a few Lines for their present Entertainment.
The Goddess thus pronounc'd her Doom:
When lo! Vanessa in her Bloom
But rarely seen, and seen from far:
In a new World with Caution stept,
Watch'd all the Company she kept;
Well knowing from the Books she read,
What dangerous paths young Virgins tread:
Wou'd Seldom at the Park appear,
Nor saw the Play-House twice a Year;
To know the Converse of Mankind.
They ask'd her how she lik'd the Play?
The told the Tattle of the Day;
A Duel fought last Night at two,
About a Lady you know who:
Talk'd of a new Italian, come
Gave Hints of who and who's together;
Then fall to talking of the Weather;
Last Night was so extreamly fine,
The Ladies walk'd till after nine.
Then in soft Voice and Speech absurd,
Run o're the Cant of stupid Lyes,
And tell the Murder of her Eyes.
